Definition: Given an entity as input, output another entity which is part of the input entity. These are entities of meronym. In linguistics, meronymy is a semantic relation between a meronym denoting a part and a holonym denoting a whole. In simpler terms, a meronym (i.e., output entity) is in a part-of relationship with its holonym (i.e., input entity).

Positive Examples.explanation: The answer is correct. Because a stem is one of two main structural axes of a vascular plant, the other being the root. Therefore, stem (i.e., meronym) is the part of plant (i.e., holonym).
Hagfish is a living thing. Therefore, heart is part of the fish. Hence, the answer is correct.
Most of the birds have feathers. Therefore, these are the entities of the meronym.
All surfaces are made of various materials. Hence, the materials are part of the surface. Hence, the answer is correct.

Pentose sugar are a form of sugar, pentose meaning 5 carbon atoms. These sugars are found in DNA/RNA which are nucleotides. Thus they are involved in a part-of relationship with nucleotides making the output correct.
Ammonia stench is commonly associated with public restrooms. This is since ammonia is a by-product of urine and thus is a meronym of urine.
This is a good example since nitrogen here can be interpreted as a 'nitrogen molecule'. Atoms are a part of every molecule by definition.

Negative Examples.explanation: Humans does not have any tails. Therefore, the answer is incorrect as tail is not the part of the human.
This is wrong answer because brick is not edible. Hence, brick is not part of any food.
The correct answer here should be aspects like eyes, nose etc. which are a part-of the face. Hamstrings on the contrary are parts of the legs.
The output incorrectly associates a disease of the liver (cirrhosis) with that of the pancreas (chronic pancreatitis). The correct answer would have been pancrea.
